]], China\n| align=\"right\" |2\n| align=\"right\" |8L\n|\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:89%; align=center;\"\n|+ '''Busiest domestic routes out of Penang International Airport by frequency'''\n|- style=\"background:darkgrey;\"\n! |Rank|| |Destinations|| |Frequency (Weekly)|| |Airlines\n|-\n|1\n|{{flagicon|Selangor}} [[Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah Airport|Subang]], Selangor (SZB) \n| align=\"right\" |170\n| align=\"right\" |FY, OD\n|-\n|2\n|{{flagicon|Kuala Lumpur}} [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur]] (KLIA) \n| align=\"right\" |157\n| align=\"right\" |AK, MH, OD\n|-\n|3\n|{{flagicon|Johor}} [[Senai International Airport|Johor Bharu]], Johor \n| align=\"right\" |45\n| align=\"right\" |AK\n|-\n|4\n|{{flagicon|Kedah}} [[Langkawi International Airport|Langkawi]], Kedah \n| align=\"right\" |39\n| align=\"right\" |AK, FY, QR\n|-\n|5\n|{{flagicon|Sabah}} [[Kota Kinabalu International Airport|Kota Kinabalu]], Sabah \n| align=\"right\" |14\n| align=\"right\" |AK\n|-\n|6\n|{{flagicon|Sarawak}} [[Kuching International Airport|Kuching]], Sarawak \n| align=\"right\" |14\n| align=\"right\" |AK\n|-\n|7\n|{{flagicon|Kelantan}} [[Sultan Ismail Petra Airport|Kota Bharu]], Kelantan \n| align=\"right\" |14\n| align=\"right\" |FY\n|-\n|8\n|{{flagicon|Malacca}} [[Melaka International Airport|Melaka]], Melaka \n| align=\"right\" |14\n| align=\"right\" |OD, AK\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:89%; align=center;\"\n|+ '''Top 10 nationalities of international arrivals (2016)'''\n|- style=\"background:darkgrey;\"\n! |Rank|| |Nationality\n!Arrivals\n|-\n|1\n|{{flagicon|Indonesia}} [[Indonesia]]\n| align=\"right\" |264,546\n|-\n|2\n|{{flagicon|Singapore}} [[Singapore]]\n| align=\"right\" |154,063\n|-\n|3\n|{{flagicon|PRC}} [[China]]\n| align=\"right\" |59,661\n|-\n|4\n|{{flagicon|Japan}} [[Japan]]\n| align=\"right\" |24,065\n|-\n|5\n|{{flagicon|Australia}} [[Australia]]\n| align=\"right\" |20,232\n|-\n|6\n|{{flagicon|USA}} [[United States]]\n| align=\"right\" |17,099\n|-\n|7\n|{{flagicon|UK}} [[United Kingdom]]\n| align=\"right\" |16,956\n|-\n|8\n|{{flagicon|Thailand}} [[Thailand]]\n| align=\"right\" |15,471\n|-\n|9\n|{{flagicon|ROC}} [[Taiwan]]\n| align=\"right\" |14,225\n|-\n|10\n|{{flagicon|India}}  [[India]]\n| align=\"right\" |7,401\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background: #f2f2f2\" |'''Total'''\n| style=\"background: #f2f2f2\" align=\"right\" |593,719\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" align=\"right\" |''Source: [[Immigration Department of Malaysia]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.buletinmutiara.com/download/2017/BuletinMutiaraJune12017-BM.pdf|title=Pulau Pinang nombor 1, hasil pelancongan perubatan 2015 naik 5.55%|date=1 June 2017|work=Buletin Mutiara|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Ground transportation==\n[[Rapid Penang]] has provided five bus routes to and from Penang International Airport, connecting the airport with various parts of [[Penang Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapidpg.com.my/journey-planner/route-maps/details/102.gif|title=Route 102|website=Rapid Penang|publisher=Rapid Penang|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapidpg.com.my/journey-planner/route-maps/details/306.gif|title=Route 306|website=Rapid Penang|publisher=Rapid Penang|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapidpg.com.my/journey-planner/route-maps/details/401.gif|title=Route 401|website=Rapid Penang|publisher=Rapid Penang|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapidpg.com.my/journey-planner/route-maps/details/at.gif|title=Rapid Penang AT Route|website=Rapid Penang|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Penang International Airport}}\n{{Portal|Malaysia|Aviation}}\n\n*[http://www.malaysiaairports.com.my/index.php?ch=17&pg=55&ac=172 Penang International Airport] at [[Malaysia Airports Holdings Berhad]]\n*{{NWS-current|WMKP}}\n*{{ASN|PEN}}\n*[http://www.penangsentral.com/penang_airport/index.htm Penang Sentral Global Website]\n\n<!--Navigation boxes--><br />\n{{Airports in Malaysia}}{{Public transport in Penang}}{{Northern Corridor Economic Region}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in Penang]]\n[[Category:Northern Corridor Economic Region]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in British Malaya]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1935]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Penang International Airport\n| nativename = <small>''Lapangan Terbang Antarabangsa Pulau Pinang''</small><br /> <small>''\n| image = Penang airport view.jpg\n| image-width = 250\n| IATA = PEN\n| ICAO = WMKP\n| WMO = 48601\n| type = Public\n| owner = [[Government of Malaysia]]\n| operator = [[Malaysia Airports]]\n| city-served = [[Greater Penang Conurbation|Greater Penang]]\n| location = Lapangan Terbang Antarabangsa Bayan Lepas, 11900 Bayan Lepas, Penang, Malaysia.\n| hub = <div>\n*[[AirAsia]]\n*[[Firefly (airline)|Firefly]]\n*[[Malaysia Airlines]]\n*[[MASkargo]]\n*[[Malindo Air]] \n</div>\n| timezone = [[Time in Malaysia|MST]]\n| utc = [[UTC+08:00]]\n| elevation-f = 11\n| coordinates = {{coord|05|17|49.7|N|100|16|36.71|E|region:MY-10|display=inline,title}}\n| website = \n| image_map = LocationMalaysia.svg\n| image_map_caption = [[Penang]] state in Malaysia\n| pushpin_map = Malaysia Penang George Town#Malaysia Penang#Malaysia West#Malaysia#Southeast Asia#Asia\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location within {{Legend inline|#fefee9|outline=silver}} '''[[George Town, Penang|George Town]]''' in {{Legend inline|#f7e2ba|outline=black}} '''[[Penang]]'''\n| pushpin_label = ''' PEN '''/WMKP\n| r1-number = 04/22\n| r1-length-m = 3,352\n| r1-surface = [[Asphalt]]\n| metric-rwy = y\n| stat1-header = Passenger\n| stat1-data = 7,790,423 ({{increase}} 7.7%)\n| stat-year = 2018\n| footnotes = \n| stat2-header = Airfreight (tonnes)\n| stat2-data = 145,649 ({{increase}} 8.5%)\n| stat3-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat3-data = 75,552 ({{increase}} 7.0%)\n}}\n\n'''Penang International Airport''' {{airport codes|PEN|WMKP}} is one of the [[List of the busiest airports in Malaysia|busiest airports in Malaysia]]. The airport is located near [[Bayan Lepas]] at the southeastern tip of [[Penang Island]], {{convert|16|km|abbr=on}} south of the city centre.<ref name=AIP>[http://aip.dca.gov.my/aip%20pdf/AD/AD2/WMKN/WMKN-Kuala%20TerangganuSultan%20Mahmud%20Airpor.pdf WMKP \u2013 PENANG INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT] at Department of Civil Aviation Malaysia</ref> Previously known as the Bayan Lepas International Airport, it was opened in 1935, making it the oldest airport in the country.\n\nPenang International Airport is a medium-sized airport with frequent connections to major cities in [[Asia]] such as [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Singapore]], [[Bangkok]], [[Jakarta]], [[Medan]], [[Hong Kong]] and [[Taipei]], and serves as the main airport for northwestern [[Malaysia]]. In addition, Penang International Airport is the [[Busiest airports in Malaysia|third-busiest airport in Malaysia]] in terms of passenger traffic and the [[List of the busiest airports in Malaysia|second-busiest]] in terms of cargo tonnage.<ref name=\"Penang International Airport\">{{cite web|url=http://www.malaysiaairports.com.my/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=351&Itemid=79|title=Malaysia Airports|accessdate=18 November 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328063834/http://www.malaysiaairports.com.my/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=351&Itemid=79|archivedate=28 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The airport is also one of the hubs of the Malaysian [[low-cost carrier]]s, [[AirAsia]] and [[Firefly (airline)|Firefly]].<ref name=btimes>{{cite news|url=http://www.btimes.com.my/articles/jkath/Article/|title=AirAsia to turn Penang into fourth hub in Malaysia|date=8 July 2009|work=The Star}} {{Dead link|date=September 2017}}</ref>\n\nPassengers arriving from the north will have a view of George Town, [[Butterworth, Penang|Butterworth]], and both the [[Penang Bridge]] and the [[Sultan Abdul Halim Muadzam Shah Bridge|Second Penang Bridge]]. Waiting times for check-in and baggage claims are relatively short compared to other larger regional airports. The airport is not crowded and basic facilities are available for users.\n\nPenang International Airport won the Best Emerging Airport (Asia) award in the 23rd annual Asian Freight and Supply Chain Awards 2009 (AFSCA), and was named the Airport of the Year (below 15 million passengers annually) in the 2009 Frost and Sullivan Asia Pacific Aerospace and Defence Awards.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Penang International Airport at night.jpg|left|thumb|Penang International Airport at night]]\nThe airport, then named Bayan Lepas International Airport, was completed in 1935, when [[Penang]] was part of the [[British crown colony]] of the [[Straits Settlements]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.skyscanner.co.in/airports/pen/penang-airport.html|title=Handy Penang airport information from Skyscanner|website=www.skyscanner.co.in|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] attacked [[Penang]] in December 1941, the airport was one of the first places to be hit by Japanese air raids.<ref>{{cite book|title=Penang at War : A History of Penang During and Between the First and Second World Wars|last=Barber|first=Andrew|publisher=AB&A|year=2010}}</ref> The Japanese sought to neutralise the [[Royal Air Force|British]] and [[Royal Australian Air Force|Australian]] air force units by targeting all airfields in [[Penang]], including [[RMAF Butterworth|RAF Butterworth]] and the Bayan Lepas International Airport.\n\nIn the 1970s, a major expansion of the airport was carried out, during which a terminal building of Minangkabau architecture was built and the runway extended to accommodate [[Boeing 747]]<nowiki/>s, then the largest passenger jet aircraft.  Upon the completion of the expansion works in 1979, the airport was renamed Penang International Airport.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe airport was renovated between 2009 and 2013, giving the terminal building a major facelift. At present, Penang International Airport is run by the national airport operator, [[Malaysia Airports|Malaysia Airports Holdings Berhad]] (MAHB).\n\n==Facilities==\n[[File:Penang airport checkin.jpg|thumb|Passenger check-in counters|left]]Penang International Airport has the capacity to handle up to 6.5 million passengers per year, while its cargo centre can handle 360,000 tonnes of cargo within the same annual period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.malaysiaairports.com.my/?m=business&c=business_about&id=18|title=International Airports|website=www.malaysiaairports.com.my|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> Its two runways are about {{convert|3.35|km||abbr=on}} in total length.\n\nThe airport also has 64 check-in desks and 11 gates, 12 aerobridges and three luggage claim belts. The terminal building houses various restaurants, boutiques and shops, as well as premium passenger lounges.\n\nThe airport became a source of contention between the [[Government of Penang|Penang state government]] and the [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian federal government]] in recent years, as transportation infrastructure throughout Malaysia falls under the purview of the latter authority. Calls by the Penang state government to expand the airport largely went unheeded by the Malaysian federal government, even though the airport has exceeded its maximum capacity of 6.5 million passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/guan-eng-demands-putrajaya-approve-penang-international-airport-expansion-n|title=Guan Eng demands Putrajaya approve Penang International Airport expansion now|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=23 September 2017}}</ref> In 2017, the federal authorities finally announced plans to expand the airport to accommodate 12 million passengers per year by 2029.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theedgemarkets.com/article/penang-international-airport-expansion-start-soon|title=Penang International Airport expansion to start soon|date=13 February 2018|work=The Edge Markets|access-date=27 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1576035/in-expansion-project-penang-airport-capacity-to-double-to-12-million-passen|title=Expansion project to double Penang airport capacity to 12 million passengers, says council head|last=Opalyn Mok|date=12 February 2018|work=[[Malay Mail]]|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport destination list\n| [[AirAsia]] |  [[Chengdu Shuangliu International Airport|Chengdu]] ,<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/288722/airasia-adds-penang-chengdu-service-in-march-2020/</ref> [[Tan Son Nhat International Airport|Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatta]], [[Senai International Airport|Johor Bahru]], [[Kota Kinabalu International Airport|Kota Kinabalu]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[Kuching International Airport|Kuching]], [[Langkawi International Airport|Langkawi]], [[Kuala Namu International Airport|Medan]], [[Melaka International Airport|Melaka]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n| [[Batik Air]] | [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatta]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/284124/batik-air-schedules-penang-service-from-late-may-2019/|title=Batik Air schedules Penang service from late-May 2019|website=Routesonline}}</ref>\n| [[Berjaya Air]] | '''Charter:''' [[Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah Airport|Kuala Lumpur-Subang]]\n| [[Cathay Dragon]] | [[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]]\n| [[China Airlines]] | [[Taiwan Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]]\n| [[Citilink]] | [[Soekarno-Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatt