-\n| 45\n| Contestants to face yet another nomination\n| {{Start date|2020|02|18}}\n| Superheroes and supervillains in the house today! The luxury budget task leaves the housemates in splits.\n|-\n| 46\n| Fukru accuses Rajith of choking him with a shawl; calls him a 'beast' while Fukru kicks Rajith on the chest\n| {{Start date|2020|02|19}}\n| As the task continues and competition gets tough, housemates make new strategies to win.\n|-\n| 47\n| Rajith and Fukru get jailed\n| {{Start date|2020|02|20}}\n| The housemates have to take decisions - not one, but two.\n|}\n\n====BB Cafe====\n''BB Cafe'' is an [[aftershow]] hosted by Rajesh Keshav and Gopika that discusses episodes aired on the previous day. Each episode is approximately five minutes long. ''BB Cafe Live'', a 30-minute live show is also aired daily on Asianet's [[YouTube]] channel that discuss the live comments on YouTube.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\n|-\n! style=\"background:#8FBC8F; color:#FFFFFF;| {{abbr|Ep. No.|Episode Number}}\n! style=\"background:#8FBC8F; color:#FFFFFF;| Title\n! style=\"background:#8FBC8F; color:#FFFFFF;| Original airing\n! style=\"background:#8FBC8F; color:#FFFFFF;| Short summary\n|-\n|1\n|The Cafe Opens\n|6 January 2020\n|Chat session with Rajesh and Gopika discuss the premiere episode.\n|-\n|2\n|All About Arya and Fukru\n|7 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika discuss Fukru's love story and Arya's cooking session in the Bigg Boss.\n|-\n|3\n|Gopika is Impressed\n|8 January 2020\n|Gopika is impressed with RJ Raghu's story. Rajesh has a personal favourite in the house.\n|-\n|4\n|Rajesh Adores Somu\n|9 January 2020\n|While Rajesh shares about Somu's musical skills, Gopika has some soft corner for Veena and Arya.\n|-\n|5\n|Rajith Faces the Jury\n|10 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika talk about Rajith's behaviour with the other contestants. They also discuss Somu's story.\n|-\n|6\n|All About the Surprise\n|11 January 2020\n|Gopika and Rajesh share their excitement about Mohanlal's entry in the house and the surprise visit of a stranger.\n|-\n|7\n|Hot Gossip\n|12 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika get together to talk about the latest and hottest news from the Bigg Boss house.\n|-\n|8\n|Crucial Moments to Come\n|13 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika discuss Mohanlal's visit to the house. They also talk about the upcoming evictions.\n|-\n|9\n|Voting Begins\n|14 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika talk about the voting. Also, explains how to vote for your favourite contestants.\n|-\n|10\n|The Countdown\n|15 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika talk about the upcoming voting at the house.\n|-\n|11\n|Latest News\n|16 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika talk about the latest news from the Bigg Boss House.\n|-\n|12\n|Unlimited Entertainment\n|17 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika join the show with hot gossip from Bigg Boss. Also, talks about the upcoming evictions.\n|-\n|13\n|All About Elimination\n|18 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika are all excited for the first elimination round. Also have a gossip chat session with the duo.\n|-\n|14\n|Mohanlal's Entry\n|19 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika share their excitement and nervousness about Mohanlal's entry and the elimination round.\n|-\n|15\n|Mohanlal's Clever Plan\n|20 January 2020\n|Praise Mohanlal's clever plan in the eviction round. Also, talks their view on the next nomination round. \n|-\n|16\n|Somadas About His Eviction\n|21 January 2020\n|Somadas talks about surprise eviction in the house. Also, share their opinion about Rajith Kumar.\n|-\n|17\n|Romance in the House\n|22 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika share their doubts about the first romance in the house.\n|-\n|18\n|All About the Luxury Task\n|23 January 2020\n|Talk about the Luxury task of the week. Also, they remind the viewers to vote for their favourite contestants.\n|-\n|19\n|Rajith's Transformation\n|24 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika are surprised to see Rajith's transformation.\n|-\n|20\n|A Major Suspense\n|25 January 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika reveal a major surprise about the upcoming eviction round.\n|-\n|21\n|Mohanlal's Visit\n|26 January 2020\n|Discuss about Mohanlal's visit to the Bigg Boss house. They also try to figure out the upcoming evictions.\n|-\n|22\n|Two Wild Card Entries\n|27 January 2020\n|Talk about the two new contestants Jasla Madassery and Daya Achu, who came through the wild card entry.\n|-\n|23\n|Fukru's Adventures\n|28 January 2020\n|Talk about Fukru's adventures in the Bigg Boss House. Also, discuss the new nominations.\n|-\n|24\n|Love is in the Air?\n|29 January 2020\n|Talk about a new budding romance in the Bigg Boss house.\n|-\n|25\n|Jazla, Rajith's Fight\n|30 January 2020\n|Talk about Jazla's argument with Rajith. Later, they discuss the next captaincy task.\n|-\n|26\n|Jailed for Poor Performance\n|31 January 2020\n|They discuss the captaincy task and talk about the contestants who were jailed for performing poorly.\n|-\n|27\n|All About the New Captain\n|1 February 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika share their opinion about the new captain in the house, Rajith Kumar.\n|-\n|28\n|Thesni's Eviction\n|2 February 2020\n|Talk about Thesni's eviction and Mohanlal's visit to the house.\n|-\n|29\n|Meet the New Contestants\n|3 February 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika share their opinion about the two new wild card entries, Pavan Gino Thomas and RJ Sooraj.\n|-\n|30\n|Nominations and More\n|4 February 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika share their expectations about the upcoming nomination round.\n|-\n|31\n|The Call Centre Task\n|5 February 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika are excited about the first day at the Call Center Task.\n|-\n|32\n|Jazla and Manju's Plan\n|6 February 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika share their doubts about Jazla and Manju's plan.\n|-\n|33\n|Rajesh Has a Doubt\n|7 February 2020\n|Rajesh has a doubt about Manju's soft corner for Rajithkumar. Gopika is super excited about Mohanlal's next entry.\n|-\n|34\n|Fukru's Khusti Session\n|8 February 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika are impressed with Fukru's special Khusti session in the house. However, they have a complaint about one contestant.\n|-\n|35\n|Mohanlal's Mass Entry\n|9 February 2020\n|Rajesh and Gopika share their excitement about Mohanlal's mass entry to the house.\n|-\n|36\n|Evictions and More\n|10 February 2020\n|Talks about the Captaincy task, the recent evictions at the Bigg Boss House, and the upcoming week.\n|-\n|37\n|New Nominations\n|11 February 2020\n|Gopika and Rajesh talk about the new nominations. They also discuss Pavan's return to the show.\n|-\n|38\n|\n|12 February 2020\n|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Website|https://www.hotstar.com/in/tv/bigg-boss/s-1510|''Bigg Boss'' on Hotstar}}\n\n{{Asianet programs}}\n{{Bigg Boss (Malayalam TV series)}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of reality television series episodes]]\n", "name_user": "Woodlot", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Bigg_Boss_(Malayalam_TV_series)_episodes"}
{"title_page": "Backpacking (travel)", "text_new": "{{About|backpacking while travelling||Backpacking (disambiguation){{!}}Backpacking}}\n<!-- PLEASE READ: This page does not concern details of individual trips. WRITE OBJECTIVELY!]] -->\n[[File:Urban backpacking.jpg|thumb|Backpackers in front of the [[Vienna State Opera]] in July 2005]]\n\n'''Backpacking''' is a form of low-cost, independent travel, often staying in inexpensive lodgings and carrying all necessary possessions in a [[backpack]]. Once seen as a marginal form of travel undertaken only through necessity, it has since become a mainstream form of tourism.<ref>{{cite journal | title=From Drifter to Gap Year Tourist Mainstreaming Backpacker Travel | journal=Annals of Tourism Research | year=2006 | first=Camille | last=Caprioglio O'Reilly | volume=33 | issue=4 | pages=998\u20131017 | doi=10.1016/j.annals.2006.04.002 }}</ref>\n\nWhile backpacker tourism is generally a form of [[youth travel]], primarily undertaken by young people during [[gap year]]s, it is also undertaken by older people during a career break or retirement. Backpackers tend to be from [[Europe]], the [[English-speaking world]] and [[Asia]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidyin/2013/12/19/out-of-israel-into-the-world/ | title=Out Of Israel, Into The World | first=David | last=Yin | work=[[Forbes]] | date=December 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nBackpacker tourism generally, but does not always, include:<ref>{{cite web | url=https://sk.sagepub.com/reference/the-sage-international-encyclopedia-of-travel-and-tourism/i2343.xml | title=Backpacker Tourism | first=Catherine | last=Kelly | via=[[SAGE Publishing]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/249023759 | title=Backpacker tourism: sustainable and purposeful? Investigating the overlap between backpacker tourism and volunteer tourism motivations | first1=Natalie | last1=Ooi | first2=Jennifer H. | last2=Laing | publisher=[[Journal of Sustainable Tourism]] | via=[[ResearchGate]] | date=March 2010}}</ref>\n* Traveling mostly via [[public transport]].\n* Using inexpensive lodging such as [[hostel]]s or [[homestay]]s.\n* A longer duration trip when compared with conventional vacations.\n* An interest in meeting locals as well as seeing sights.\n* An interest in meeting other travelers.\n* Use of [[smartphone]]s and online resources for planning.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Backpackers' experiences with smartphones usage in Ghana | journal=Anatolia | volume=30 | issue=3 | pages=390\u2013403 | first=Frederick | last=Dayour | date=27 March 2019| doi=10.1080/13032917.2019.1597741 }}</ref>\n* Carrying belongings in a [[backpack]]. Backpackers have traditionally carried their possessions in 30 liter to 60 liter backpacks, but roller-wheeled suitcases and some less-traditional carrying methods, like wheeled backpacks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kesitoandfro.com/best-travel-backpack-with-wheels|title=Best Travel Backpack with Wheels|last=|first=|date=2020|website=Kesi To and Fro|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> have become more common, and there has been a trend towards keeping pack weights under the 8-to-10 kilogram carry-on limit of most airlines.<ref>\n{{cite news | first=Susan | last=Catto | title=PRACTICAL TRAVELER; The 'Pack' Of Backpacking | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/14/travel/practical-traveler-the-pack-of-backpacking.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 14, 2002 | url-access=subscription | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n* Backpacker tourism may also include working in various countries for short stints, depending on [[work permit]] laws.<ref name=BTAP>{{cite web | last=Victoria | first=Government | title=Backpacker Tourism Action Plan | url=https://www.business.vic.gov.au/tourism-industry-resources | publisher=Tourism Victoria}}</ref> It can also be undertaken by [[digital nomad]]s, people who work using technology while living a nomadic lifestyle.\n* A sense of [[authenticity (philosophy)|authenticity]]. Backpacking is perceived not only as a form of [[tourism]], but a means of education.<ref>{{cite journal | title=A \"University of Travel\": Backpacker Learning | journal=Tourism Management | year=2007 | first1=Philip | last1=Pearce | first2=Faith | last2=Foster | volume=28 | issue=5 | pages=1285\u20131298 | doi=10.1016/j.tourman.2006.11.009}}\n</ref> Backpackers want to experience what they consider the \"real\" destination rather than a packaged version often associated with mass tourism.<ref>{{cite book | last1=Richards | first1=Greg | first2=Julie | last2=Wilson | title=The Global Nomad: Backpacker Theory in Travel and Practice | publisher=[[Channel View Publications]] | pages=80\u201391 | url =https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Global_Nomad.html?id=S8qBAAAAMAAJ | isbn=1-873150-76-8 | date=March 29, 2004}}\n</ref>\n\n==History==\nPeople have travelled for thousands of years with their possessions on their backs, but usually out of need rather than for recreation.\n\nIn the 17th century, Italian adventurer [[Giovanni Francesco Gemelli Careri]] was likely one of the first people to engage in backpacker tourism.<ref>{{cite news | title=The Inventor of Traveling - The First Backpacker in the World? | date=July 2007 | url=http://www.infohostels.com/notizia.php?chiave=200 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212000017/http://www.infohostels.com/notizia.php?chiave=200 | archivedate=12 December 2007 | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n\nThe modern popularity of backpacking can be traced, at least partially, to the [[hippie trail]] of the 1960s and 1970s,<ref name=Diversity>{{cite journal | title=Backpacking: Diversity and Change | journal=Tourism and Cultural Change | year=2003 | first=Erik | last=Cohen | volume=1 | issue=2 | pages=95\u2013110 | doi=10.1080/14766820308668162}}</ref> which in turn followed sections of the old [[Silk Road]]. Some backpackers follow the same trail today.<ref>\n{{cite news | first=Jennifer | last=Conlin | title=IN TRANSIT; Traveling to the Ends of the Earth, at Ground Level | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/11/travel/11transbus.html?sec=travel | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 11, 2007 | url-access=subscription | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n\nSince the late-20th century, backpackers have visited [[Southeast Asia]] in large numbers<ref>{{cite web | title=Travel & Tourism Economic Impact 2018 South East Asia | url=https://www.wttc.org/-/media/files/reports/economic-impact-research/regions-2018/southeastasia2018.pdf | website=World Travel & Tourism Council | publisher=World Travel & Tourism Council}}</ref>\n\n===Benefits===\nA 2018 study of over 500 backpackers conducted by researchers at [[Sun Yat-sen University]] and [[Shaanxi Normal University]] in China and [[Edith Cowan University]] in Australia showed that for Westerners, backpacking leads to acquired capabilities like effective communication, [[decision-making]], [[adaptability]], and [[problem solving]], all of which contribute to an increase in [[self-efficacy]], and for Chinese backpackers, acquiring skills like time and [[money management]], language development, [[stress management]], and self-motivation provided the biggest increase in self-efficacy.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/travel-news/backpacking-better-more-successful-person | title=How a Backpacking Trip Could Make You a More Successful Person | first=TALIA | last=AVAKIAN | work=[[Travel + Leisure]] | date=August 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title=Backpacker Personal Development, Generalized Self-Efficacy, and Self-Esteem: Testing a Structural Model | first1=Ganghua | last1=Chen | first2=Songshan (Sam) | last2=Huang | first3=Xianyang | last3=Hu | journal=[[Journal of Travel Research]] | volume=58 | issue=4 | pages=680\u2013694 | date=May 3, 2018| doi=10.1177/0047287518768457 }}</ref>\n\nFor many low-income communities in the developing world, the economic benefits of hosting backpackers outweigh their negative impacts. Since backpackers tend to consume local products, stay in small guest houses, and use locally owned ground transport, more of their expenditure is retained in-country than in conventional mass tourism. businesses that cater to backpackers are usually locally owned and profits tend to be retained within the country rather than flowing overseas to international hotel groups.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/sep/24/backpacker-travel-benefit-poor-countries | title=Backpacker tourism can be beneficial for poor countries | first=Mark | last=Hampton | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=September 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\nBackpacker tourism of the [[hippie trail]] has been criticized for possibly encouraging urban liberal minorities while insulting [[Traditionalist theology (Islam)|Islamic traditionalist theology]], possibly leading to the Islamic reawakening in the late 1970s.<ref>{{cite news | first=Rory | last=MacLean | title=Dark Side of the Hippie Trail | url=https://www.newstatesman.com/node/164904 | work=[[The New Statesman]] | date=July 31, 2006 | url-status= live}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KmlYvgEACAAJ | title=Magic Bus: On the Hippie Trail from Istanbul to India | first=Rory | last=MacLean | publisher=[[Ig Publishing]] | date=2009| isbn=9780978843199 }}</ref>\n\nEven though one of the primary aims of backpacking is to seek the \"authentic\", the majority of backpackers spend most of their time interacting with other backpackers, and interactions with locals are of \"secondary importance\".<ref name=Diversity/>\n\nBackpacker tourism has been criticized for the transformation of some sleepy towns, such as the creation of the [[Full Moon Party]] on [[Ko Pha-ngan]] in [[Thailand]], which includes \"scores of topless teenagers urinating into the ocean\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2010/sep/06/gap-year-thailand-full-moon-party | title=Gap years: Wasted youth? | first=Patrick | last=Kingsley | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=September 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n'''Flashpacking''' and '''Poshpacking''' refer to backpacking with more money and resources. The words combine ''backpacking'' with ''flash'', a slang term for being fancy, or ''posh'', an informal adjective for [[upper class]].<ref>{{cite news | first=Ben | last=Groundwater | title=Are you a backpacker, or a poshpacker? | url=http://blogs.smh.com.au/travel/archives/2007/01/are_you_a_backpacker_or_a_posh.html | work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | date=January 16, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title='Flashpacking?' Don't Forget you Still Need Room for Extra Socks | url=https://www.usatoday.com/travel/destinations/2006-06-19-flashpacking_x.htm | agency=[[Associated Press]] | publisher=[[USA Today]] | date=June 20, 2006}}</ref>\n\n'''Begpacking''' combines ''begging'' and ''backpacking'' in reference to individuals who [[Begging|beg]] (ask directly or indirectly for money), solicit money during [[street performance]]s, or vend (sell postcards or other small items) as a way to extend their overseas travel.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Bernstein | first=J.D. | year=2019 | title=Begging to travel: Begpacking in Southeast Asia. | journal=Annals of Tourism Research | volume=77 | pages=77, 161\u2013163 | doi=10.1016/j.annals.2018.12.014 }}</ref> The trend has drawn criticism for taking money away from people in actual need, with one known begpacker barred from entering [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Notorious begpacker barred from entering S'pore, goes around the world begging | date=April 13, 2017 | url=https://mothership.sg/2017/04/notorious-begpacker-barred-from-entering-spore/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/329837273 | title=Begging to travel: Begpacking in Southeast Asia | first=Joshua D. | last=Bernstein | date=December 2018}}</ref> Begpacking is most common in Southeast Asia and is a growing trend in South America.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/shortcuts/2019/jul/22/young-entitled-and-over-there-the-rise-of-the-begpacker | title=Young, entitled, and over there: The rise of the begpacker | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=July 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://medium.com/@MajSB/begpackers-seen-by-a-third-worldist-585d408db401 | title=Begpackers seen by a third-worldist | first=Majda | last=Saidi | work=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] | date=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary-inline|backpacking}}\n<!-- PLEASE READ: Commercial links not expanding on the article do NOT belong here.. [[Wikipedia:External links]] -->\n\n<!-- EXTERNAL LINKS SHOULD FILL THE FOLLOWING CRITERIA:\n* Be based wholly about the domain of backpacking (independent travel) and not other forms of travel,\n* Be non-Commercial with no external, banner/other ads or be linked to a commercial organisation in anyway,\n* Be recognised as expanding on the article and field of the article\n* Be maintained and up-to date.\n* BLOGS, TRAVEL-LOGS, TRIP BASE SITES - and similar do not belong here, nor does anything commercial such as Lonely Planet et al.\n[[Wikipedia:External links]] -->\n\n{{Wikivoyage-inline|Urban backpacking}}\n\n{{Tourism}}\n{{Adventure travel}}\n{{Orienteering}}\n\n<!-- REMEMBER: Commercial links not expanding on the article do NOT belong here.. [[Wikipedia:External links]] -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Backpacker tourism}}\n[[Category:Backpacking|*]]\n[[Category:Youth hostelling]]\n[[Category:Hitchhiking]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|backpacking while travelling||Backpacking (disambiguation){{!}}Backpacking}}\n<!-- PLEASE READ: This page does not concern details of individual trips. WRITE OBJECTIVELY!]] -->\n[[File:Urban backpacking.jpg|thumb|Backpackers in front of the [[Vienna State Opera]] in July 2005]]\n\n'''Backpacking''' is a form of low-cost, independent travel, often staying in inexpensive lodgings and carrying all necessary possessions in a [[backpack]]. Once seen as a marginal form of travel undertaken only through necessity, it has since become a mainstream form of tourism.<ref>{{cite journal | title=From Drifter to Gap Year Tourist Mainstreaming Backpacker Travel | journal=Annals of Tourism Research | year=2006 | first=Camille | last=Caprioglio O'Reilly | volume=33 | issue=4 | pages=998\u20131017 | doi=10.1016/j.annals.2006.04.002 }}</ref>\n\nWhile backpacker tourism is generally a form of [[youth travel]], primarily undertaken by young people during [[gap year]]s, it is also undertaken by older people during a career break or retirement. Backpackers tend to be from [[Europe]], the [[English-speaking world]] and [[Asia]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidyin/2013/12/19/out-of-israel-into-the-world/ | title=Out Of Israel, Into The World | first=David | last=Yin | work=[[Forbes]] | date=December 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\nBackpacker tourism generally, but does not always, include:<ref>{{cite web | url=https://sk.sagepub.com/reference/the-sage-international-encyclopedia-of-travel-and-tourism/i2343.xml | title=Backpacker Tourism | first=Catherine | last=Kelly | via=[[SAGE Publishing]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/249023759 | title=Backpacker tourism: sustainable and purposeful? Investigating the overlap between backpacker tourism and volunteer tourism motivations | first1=Natalie | last1=Ooi | first2=Jennifer H. | last2=Laing | publisher=[[Journal of Sustainable Tourism]] | via=[[ResearchGate]] | date=March 2010}}</ref>\n* Traveling mostly via [[public transport]].\n* Using inexpensive lodging such as [[hostel]]s or [[homestay]]s.\n* A longer duration trip when compared with conventional vacations.\n* An interest in meeting locals as well as seeing sights.\n* An interest in meeting other travelers.\n* Use of [[smartphone]]s and online resources for planning.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Backpackers' experiences with smartphones usage in Ghana | journal=Anatolia | volume=30 | issue=3 | pages=390\u2013403 | first=Frederick | last=Dayour | date=27 March 2019| doi=10.1080/13032917.2019.1597741 }}</ref>\n* Carrying belongings in a [[backpack]]. Backpackers have traditionally carried their possessions in 30 liter to 60 liter backpacks, but roller-wheeled suitcases and some less-traditional carrying methods have become more common, and there has been a trend towards keeping pack weights under the 8-to-10 kilogram carry-on limit of most airlines.<ref>\n{{cite news | first=Susan | last=Catto | title=PRACTICAL TRAVELER; The 'Pack' Of Backpacking | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/14/travel/practical-traveler-the-pack-of-backpacking.html | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 14, 2002 | url-access=subscription | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n* Backpacker tourism may also include working in various countries for short stints, depending on [[work permit]] laws.<ref name=BTAP>{{cite web | last=Victoria | first=Government | title=Backpacker Tourism Action Plan | url=https://www.business.vic.gov.au/tourism-industry-resources | publisher=Tourism Victoria}}</ref> It can also be undertaken by [[digital nomad]]s, people who work using technology while living a nomadic lifestyle.\n* A sense of [[authenticity (philosophy)|authenticity]]. Backpacking is perceived not only as a form of [[tourism]], but a means of education.<ref>{{cite journal | title=A \"University of Travel\": Backpacker Learning | journal=Tourism Management | year=2007 | first1=Philip | last1=Pearce | first2=Faith | last2=Foster | volume=28 | issue=5 | pages=1285\u20131298 | doi=10.1016/j.tourman.2006.11.009}}\n</ref> Backpackers want to experience what they consider the \"real\" destination rather than a packaged version often associated with mass tourism.<ref>{{cite book | last1=Richards | first1=Greg | first2=Julie | last2=Wilson | title=The Global Nomad: Backpacker Theory in Travel and Practice | publisher=[[Channel View Publications]] | pages=80\u201391 | url =https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Global_Nomad.html?id=S8qBAAAAMAAJ | isbn=1-873150-76-8 | date=March 29, 2004}}\n</ref>\n\n==History==\nPeople have travelled for thousands of years with their possessions on their backs, but usually out of need rather than for recreation.\n\nIn the 17th century, Italian adventurer [[Giovanni Francesco Gemelli Careri]] was likely one of the first people to engage in backpacker tourism.<ref>{{cite news | title=The Inventor of Traveling - The First Backpacker in the World? | date=July 2007 | url=http://www.infohostels.com/notizia.php?chiave=200 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212000017/http://www.infohostels.com/notizia.php?chiave=200 | archivedate=12 December 2007 | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n\nThe modern popularity of backpacking can be traced, at least partially, to the [[hippie trail]] of the 1960s and 1970s,<ref name=Diversity>{{cite journal | title=Backpacking: Diversity and Change | journal=Tourism and Cultural Change | year=2003 | first=Erik | last=Cohen | volume=1 | issue=2 | pages=95\u2013110 | doi=10.1080/14766820308668162}}</ref> which in turn followed sections of the old [[Silk Road]]. Some backpackers follow the same trail today.<ref>\n{{cite news | first=Jennifer | last=Conlin | title=IN TRANSIT; Traveling to the Ends of the Earth, at Ground Level | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/11/travel/11transbus.html?sec=travel | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=February 11, 2007 | url-access=subscription | url-status=live}}\n</ref>\n\nSince the late-20th century, backpackers have visited [[Southeast Asia]] in large numbers<ref>{{cite web | title=Travel & Tourism Economic Impact 2018 South East Asia | url=https://www.wttc.org/-/media/files/reports/economic-impact-research/regions-2018/southeastasia2018.pdf | website=World Travel & Tourism Council | publisher=World Travel & Tourism Council}}</ref>\n\n===Benefits===\nA 2018 study of over 500 backpackers conducted by researchers at [[Sun Yat-sen University]] and [[Shaanxi Normal University]] in China and [[Edith Cowan University]] in Australia showed that for Westerners, backpacking leads to acquired capabilities like effective communication, [[decision-making]], [[adaptability]], and [[problem solving]], all of which contribute to an increase in [[self-efficacy]], and for Chinese backpackers, acquiring skills like time and [[money management]], language development, [[stress management]], and self-motivation provided the biggest increase in self-efficacy.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.travelandleisure.com/travel-news/backpacking-better-more-successful-person | title=How a Backpacking Trip Could Make You a More Successful Person | first=TALIA | last=AVAKIAN | work=[[Travel + Leisure]] | date=August 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title=Backpacker Personal Development, Generalized Self-Efficacy, and Self-Esteem: Testing a Structural Model | first1=Ganghua | last1=Chen | first2=Songshan (Sam) | last2=Huang | first3=Xianyang | last3=Hu | journal=[[Journal of Travel Research]] | volume=58 | issue=4 | pages=680\u2013694 | date=May 3, 2018| doi=10.1177/0047287518768457 }}</ref>\n\nFor many low-income communities in the developing world, the economic benefits of hosting backpackers outweigh their negative impacts. Since backpackers tend to consume local products, stay in small guest houses, and use locally owned ground transport, more of their expenditure is retained in-country than in conventional mass tourism. businesses that cater to backpackers are usually locally owned and profits tend to be retained within the country rather than flowing overseas to international hotel groups.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/sep/24/backpacker-travel-benefit-poor-countries | title=Backpacker tourism can be beneficial for poor countries | first=Mark | last=Hampton | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=September 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Criticism===\nBackpacker tourism of the [[hippie trail]] has been criticized for possibly encouraging urban liberal minorities while insulting [[Traditionalist theology (Islam)|Islamic traditionalist theology]], possibly leading to the Islamic reawakening in the late 1970s.<ref>{{cite news | first=Rory | last=MacLean | title=Dark Side of the Hippie Trail | url=https://www.newstatesman.com/node/164904 | work=[[The New Statesman]] | date=July 31, 2006 | url-status= live}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KmlYvgEACAAJ | title=Magic Bus: On the Hippie Trail from Istanbul to India | first=Rory | last=MacLean | publisher=[[Ig Publishing]] | date=2009| isbn=9780978843199 }}</ref>\n\nEven though one of the primary aims of backpacking is to seek the \"authentic\", the majority of backpackers spend most of their time interacting with other backpackers, and interactions with locals are of \"secondary importance\".<ref name=Diversity/>\n\nBackpacker tourism has been criticized for the transformation of some sleepy towns, such as the creation of the [[Full Moon Party]] on [[Ko Pha-ngan]] in [[Thailand]], which includes \"scores of topless teenagers urinating into the ocean\".<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/2010/sep/06/gap-year-thailand-full-moon-party | title=Gap years: Wasted youth? | first=Patrick | last=Kingsley | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=September 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n'''Flashpacking''' and '''Poshpacking''' refer to backpacking with more money and resources. The words combine ''backpacking'' with ''flash'', a slang term for being fancy, or ''posh'', an informal adjective for [[upper class]].<ref>{{cite news | first=Ben | last=Groundwater | title=Are you a backpacker, or a poshpacker? | url=http://blogs.smh.com.au/travel/archives/2007/01/are_you_a_backpacker_or_a_posh.html | work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | date=January 16, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title='Flashpacking?' Don't Forget you Still Need Room for Extra Socks | url=https://www.usatoday.com/travel/destinations/2006-06-19-flashpacking_x.htm | agency=[[Associated Press]] | publisher=[[USA Today]] | date=June 20, 2006}}</ref>\n\n'''Begpacking''' combines ''begging'' and ''backpacking'' in reference to individuals who [[Begging|beg]] (ask directly or indirectly for money), solicit money during [[street performance]]s, or vend (sell postcards or other small items) as a way to extend their overseas travel.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Bernstein | first=J.D. | year=2019 | title=Begging to travel: Begpacking in Southeast Asia. | journal=Annals of Tourism Research | volume=77 | pages=77, 161\u2013163 | doi=10.1016/j.annals.2018.12.014 }}</ref> The trend has drawn criticism for taking money away from people in actual need, with one known begpacker barred from entering [[Singapore]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Notorious begpacker barred from entering S'pore, goes around the world begging | date=April 13, 2017 | url=https://mothership.sg/2017/04/notorious-begpacker-barred-from-entering-spore/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/329837273 | title=Begging to travel: Begpacking in Southeast Asia | first=Joshua D. | last=Bernstein | date=December 2018}}</ref> Begpacking is most common in Southeast Asia and is a growing trend in South America.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/travel/shortcuts/2019/jul/22/young-entitled-and-over-there-the-rise-of-the-begpacker | title=Young, entitled, and over there: The rise of the begpacker | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=July 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://medium.com/@MajSB/begpackers-seen-by-a-third-worldist-585d408db401 | title=Begpackers seen by a third-worldist | first=Majda | last=Saidi | work=[[Medium (website)|Medium]] | date=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary-inline|backpacking}}\n<!-- PLEASE READ: Commercial links not expanding on the article do NOT belong here.. [[Wikipedia:External links]] -->\n\n<!-- EXTERNAL LINKS SHOULD FILL THE FOLLOWING CRITERIA:\n* Be based wholly about the domain of backpacking (independent travel) and not other forms of travel,\n* Be non-Commercial with no external, banner/other ads or be linked to a commercial organisation in anyway,\n* Be recognised as expanding on the article and field of the article\n* Be maintained and up-to date.\n* BLOGS, TRAVEL-LOGS, TRIP BASE SITES - and similar do not belong here, nor does anything commercial such as Lonely Planet et al.\n[[Wikipedia:External links]] -->\n\n{{Wikivoyage-inline|Urban backpacking}}\n\n{{Tourism}}\n{{Adventure travel}}\n{{Orienteering}}\n\n<!-- REMEMBER: Commercial links not expanding on the article do NOT belong here.. [[Wikipedia:External links]] -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Backpacker tourism}}\n[[Category:Backpacking|*]]\n[[Category:Youth hostelling]]\n[[Category:Hitchhiking]]\n", "name_user": "Nerdgirrl101", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(edited citation)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backpacking_(travel)"}
